div.div: This unit is fill from a pit in space 244. The excavators reported charcoal, burnt plaster, clay, and animal bone, and suggested that this might be a cooking pit or a pit for disposal of cooking refuse. The dry sieved portion of this unit is a smallish sample of primarily sheep-sized material, with a large minority of cow-sized material. The cow-sized and Bos fragments in this unit are very large, around ten centimetres on average, and are mostly burnt. Sheep-sized material includes long bone, rib, and vertebral fragments. Cow-sized material includes long bone shaft fragments, ribs, and scapular fragments. Diagnostics overwhelmingly dominate the unit (ca. 70%). In the small amount of scrap, long bone shaft fragments do not dominate in either size range, as they do in other units: though there are more long bone shaft fragments than rib fragments, the ratio is lower than normal. However, the sample size is small. All diagnostics from the sample are caprine or Bos. Caprine material includes several fragments from the forelimb, a carpal and phalange from the feet, and a few fragments of skull and teeth. There are no caprine hindlimb fragments. Bos material includes fragments from fore and hind limb and feet, but there are not enough to look at body part distribution. The weathering is variable, with a lot of surface condition four caused by wind and sun, trampling, and digestion, and some surface condition three, so it is difficult to see cut marks or other traces of food processing. However, the sample includes fragments from differentially valuable body parts, including the high-yield limbs as well as a few fragments of feet and mandible/teeth. There are two long bone fragments with impact fractures from probable marrow processing as well as a rib shaft with filleting marks. About 15% of the material is burnt, most of it carbonized, with a few small fragments of calcined bone. The carbonized-burnt material is the larger fragments in the unit: the Bos fragments and cow-sized scrap and a caprine scapula. Other taphonomic traces indicate that not all of the sample was primary disposal: a few of the long bone shaft fragments are trampled/rolled, there is one fragment of possibly digested bone, and three fragments that appear to be gnawed by carnivores. All of the fragments affected by carnivores are three cm or smaller. This unit appears to have a modal distribution in terms of treatment. There are several one and two cm fragments, many of which were affected by trampling or carnivores. These small fragments are the only bones affected by trampling/carnivores. There are several fragments between two and six cm, most of which have new breaks. These fragments are largely unburnt and include most of the caprine material. Then there are some quite long or large fragments, including a rib that, despite new break, is 17 cm long. The larger fragments include almost all of the carbonized material. These fragments are not marked by cuts or impact fractures. If this unit was a primary cooking pit, the small filly fragments are oddly unburnt -- the carbonized bones are the large bones, not the small incidentals. There is no evidence that the bones were burnt in this pit. If this unit is a pit for the disposal of special meals, there is a fair amount of probably unrelated refuse buried as well, though the fragments of carpals and tarsals and the smaller fragments with multiple origins could also be background noise from pit fill. The interesting thing about the unit is the difference between cattle and caprine processing and fragments, with large fragments of burnt cattle and a possibly valued caprine scapula, and smaller fragments of unburnt caprine. The flot sample from this unit is a large flotation sample (sample #1, >4mm, 100% sorted, flot 5943, recorded completely). The sample is mostly sheep-sized scrap, and looks like background noise with the possible exception of a couple pieces of larger bone, including several antler fragments that were almost certainly one fragment in the ground. There is also a fragment of a bone tool, ample rodent (very modern-appearing) as well as a few pieces of amphibian microfauna, four fragments of fish bone, and a few bird bone fragments. Sheep-sized material includes long bone shaft, rib, vertebral, and cranial fragments. There are also a few hare-sized long bone shaft fragments and one cow-sized vertebral fragment. There are few diagnostics. Most diagnostics are caprine, including a few fragments each from forelimb, feet, and skull. There are not enough caprine fragments to discuss body part distribution. Other diagnostics include the fragments of antler and a burnt pig canine. Taphonomically, the flot sample is distinct from the dry sieved sample in several ways. Most of the flot sample is one cm long (ca 90%), with most remaining fragments (ca. 8%) two or three cm. There are only six fragments that are five to six cm. More of this sample is burnt than the dry sieve: about half of the indet fragments are burnt, mostly carbonized with a few calcined fragments. There is also a small amount of digested bone (<2%) and of gnawed bone (<5%), and some trampled/rolled bone (<10%). The fragments are in mixed good condition, mostly surface condition three with some four. The surface condition four is due to sun, digestion, and trampling. The flot sample has low integrity/coherence, mostly looking like filly background noise, as some bone has been worked over by carnivores, some has been trampled, and some has spent time exposed to sun and wind. However, the pig canine may fit into the carbonized large or possibly special bones of the dry sieved material.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
